<h2>Energy Efficiency and Cooling Cost Savings</h2>
<p><strong>How tile reduces your electric bills.</strong></p>
<h3>Thermal Mass Properties</h3>
<p><strong>Why heavy materials save energy:</strong></p>
<p><strong>Thermal mass</strong> = material&#39;s ability to absorb, store, and slowly release heat</p>
<p><strong>Tile roofing (7-10 lbs per sq ft):</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Absorbs solar heat during day (prevents immediate transfer to attic/home)</li>
<li>Stores heat within tile mass</li>
<li>Releases heat slowly during evening and night</li>
<li><strong>Creates time-lag effect reducing peak cooling loads</strong></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Shingle roofing (2-3 lbs per sq ft):</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Minimal thermal mass</li>
<li>Heat transfers quickly through thin shingle to attic</li>
<li>Attic temperatures reach 140-160°F on summer days</li>
<li>HVAC works continuously to combat heat gain</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Real-world impact:</strong></p>
<p><strong>Attic temperature at 3pm (95°F outside temperature):</strong></p>
<p>With shingle roof:</p>
<ul>
<li>Attic temperature: 145-155°F</li>
<li>Heat radiating into home despite insulation</li>
<li>AC runs constantly</li>
</ul>
<p>With tile roof:</p>
<ul>
<li>Attic temperature: 120-130°F (20-25°F cooler)</li>
<li>Reduced heat transfer to living spaces</li>
<li>AC cycles less frequently</li>
</ul>
<h3>Air Space Insulation Effect</h3>
<p><strong>Tile installation creates air gap:</strong></p>
<p><strong>Standard tile installation:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Battens (wood strips) attached to roof deck</li>
<li>Tiles hung on battens</li>
<li><strong>1-2 inch air space between tile and underlayment</strong></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Air space benefits:</strong></p>
<p>✓ Natural convection cooling (hot air rises through ridge vent)
✓ Additional insulation layer (R-2 to R-3 value from air space)
✓ Prevents direct contact between hot tile and roof substrate
✓ Allows moisture to escape (roof deck stays dry)</p>
<p><strong>Combined effect with thermal mass:</strong></p>
<p>Tile + air space = <strong>25-30% cooling cost reduction</strong> compared to shingle roofs</p>
<p><strong>Annual savings calculation:</strong></p>
<p><strong>Typical 2,000 sq ft South Florida home:</strong></p>
<p><strong>With shingle roof:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Annual cooling cost: $2,400</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>With tile roof:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Annual cooling cost: $1,700-1,800</li>
<li><strong>Savings: $600-700 per year</strong></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Over 50 years: $30,000-35,000 in energy savings</strong></p>
<h3>Reflective Coatings and Cool Roof Options</h3>
<p><strong>Cool tile technology:</strong></p>
<p>Many modern concrete tiles feature <strong>cool roof coatings:</strong></p>
<p>✓ Solar reflectance: 0.60-0.70 (reflects 60-70% of solar radiation)
✓ Thermal emittance: 0.75-0.85 (releases absorbed heat efficiently)
✓ ENERGY STAR certification available
✓ Qualifies for FPL Cool Roof rebates (up to $1,700)</p>
<p><strong>Color impact on energy efficiency:</strong></p>
<p><strong>Light colors (white, light gray, terra cotta):</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Solar reflectance: 0.60-0.75</li>
<li>Maximum cooling benefits</li>
<li>Most energy-efficient choice</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Medium colors (brown, rust, medium gray):</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Solar reflectance: 0.40-0.55</li>
