<h2>Concrete vs Clay Tile: Detailed Comparison</h2>
<p><strong>Choosing between the two tile types.</strong></p>
<h3>Performance Characteristics</h3>
<p><strong>Hurricane resistance:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Concrete: Excellent (Miami-Dade NOA approved, 180mph ratings)</li>
<li>Clay: Excellent (identical wind ratings when properly installed)</li>
<li><strong>Winner: Tie</strong> (both meet HVHZ requirements)</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Lifespan:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Concrete: 40-50 years typical</li>
<li>Clay: 50-75 years typical</li>
<li><strong>Winner: Clay</strong> (10-25 years longer, though both exceed alternatives)</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Energy efficiency:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Concrete: Excellent (thermal mass, air space, cool coatings available)</li>
<li>Clay: Excellent (slightly better thermal properties, lower conductivity)</li>
<li><strong>Winner: Clay (slight edge)</strong> — 2-5% better energy performance</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Weight:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Concrete: 8-10 lbs per square foot</li>
<li>Clay: 7-9 lbs per square foot</li>
<li><strong>Winner: Clay (slightly lighter)</strong> — May reduce structural reinforcement needs</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Water absorption:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Concrete: 10-15% absorption rate</li>
<li>Clay: 3-7% absorption rate</li>
<li><strong>Winner: Clay</strong> (though South Florida&#39;s lack of freeze-thaw cycles makes this less relevant)</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Color retention:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Concrete: Good (pigments throughout tile, some fading over decades)</li>
<li>Clay: Excellent (natural terra cotta color, minimal fading)</li>
<li><strong>Winner: Clay</strong> (better long-term color retention)</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Cost:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Concrete: $12-16 per sq ft installed</li>
<li>Clay: $18-25 per sq ft installed</li>
<li><strong>Winner: Concrete</strong> (40-60% less expensive)</li>
</ul>
<h3>Aesthetic Considerations</h3>
<p><strong>Concrete tile advantages:</strong></p>
<p>✓ <strong>Wide range of colors</strong> — Dozens of colors available (earth tones to grays)
✓ <strong>Multiple profiles</strong> — Flat, low profile, medium profile, high profile (barrel)
✓ <strong>Modern or traditional</strong> — Works with contemporary or Mediterranean architecture
✓ <strong>Consistency</strong> — Uniform appearance (all tiles identical color)</p>
<p><strong>Clay tile advantages:</strong></p>
<p>✓ <strong>Authentic terra cotta appearance</strong> — Traditional Mediterranean aesthetic
✓ <strong>Natural color variation</strong> — Each tile slightly different (artisan character)
✓ <strong>Premium positioning</strong> — Luxury home standard
✓ <strong>Historic authenticity</strong> — Matches historic Spanish Colonial architecture</p>
<p><strong>Which to choose:</strong></p>
<p><strong>Choose concrete if:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Budget is primary concern ($8,000-12,000 savings on typical home)</li>
<li>Modern home or non-traditional architecture</li>
<li>Prefer uniform, consistent appearance</li>
<li>Want specific non-terra-cotta color (gray, brown, multi-blend)</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Choose clay if:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Luxury home or historic property</li>
<li>Mediterranean/Spanish Colonial architecture demands authenticity</li>
<li>Budget allows for premium materials</li>
<li>Prioritize maximum lifespan (50-75 years vs 40-50)</li>
<li>Prefer natural material with character and variation</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>South Florida reality:</strong></p>
<p>85-90% of homeowners choose concrete tile because performance is virtually identical to clay, but cost is 40-60% lower, making it the practical choice for most residential applications.</p>
<hr>
<h2>Installation Complexity and Contractor Selection</h2>
<p><strong>Why tile requires specialized expertise.</strong></p>
<h3>HVHZ Installation Requirements</h3>
<p><strong>Critical installation specifications:</strong></p>
<p><strong>1. Structural evaluation:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Verify roof framing can support 8-10 lbs/sq ft tile weight</li>
<li>May require rafter reinforcement if upgrading from shingles</li>
<li>Engineer evaluation sometimes required by building departments</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>2. Underlayment (two layers in HVHZ):</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Base layer: Self-adhering waterproof underlayment</li>
<li>Top layer: Synthetic underlayment or approved felt</li>
<li>Proper overlap and sealing at all seams</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>3. Batten installation (for some tile types):</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Horizontal wood strips attached to deck</li>
<li>Provides ventilation space beneath tiles</li>
<li>Must meet spacing specifications for tile profile</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>4. Foam adhesive application:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>HVHZ-approved polyurethane foam</li>
<li>Applied in prescribed pattern (not full coverage, specific ribbons)</li>
<li>Allows proper expansion and curing</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>5. Mechanical fastening:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Every tile mechanically attached (nails or screws)</li>
<li>Fastener type and length specified by NOA</li>
<li>Penetrates through tile, underlayment, into deck minimum 3/4&quot;</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>6. Hip and ridge details:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Special attachment requirements (maximum wind uplift zones)</li>
<li>Mortar or foam securing ridge tiles</li>
<li>Enhanced fastening patterns</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>7. Valley construction:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Metal valley liners required</li>
<li>Specific tile cutting and fitting requirements</li>
<li>Proper weave or closed valley techniques</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Inexperienced contractors often miss:</strong></p>
<p>✗ Insufficient foam adhesive coverage
✗ Wrong fastener types or lengths
✗ Inadequate underlayment overlap
✗ Improper valley construction (leads to leaks)
✗ Missing structural evaluation (roof can&#39;t support tile weight)</p>
<p><strong>Result of poor installation:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Failed building inspections</li>
<li>Voided manufacturer warranty</li>
<li>Insurance claim denials (after hurricane damage)</li>
<li>Tile blow-off during moderate storms (60-80mph winds)</li>
</ul>
<h3>Contractor Vetting Questions</h3>
<p><strong>Questions to ask tile roofing contractors:</strong></p>
<p><strong>1. Experience and licensing:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>&quot;How many tile roofs have you installed in the past 5 years?&quot;</li>
<li>&quot;Are you a licensed CCC (Certified Roofing Contractor) or CGC (General Contractor)?&quot;</li>
<li>&quot;Can you provide references from recent HVHZ tile installations?&quot;</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>2. HVHZ expertise:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>&quot;What foam adhesive products do you use, and are they Miami-Dade approved?&quot;</li>
<li>&quot;Can you explain your underlayment installation process for HVHZ?&quot;</li>
<li>&quot;How do you ensure proper hip and ridge attachment for 180mph wind ratings?&quot;</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>3. Warranty and insurance:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>&quot;What workmanship warranty do you provide?&quot; (Minimum 5 years, 10 years preferred)</li>
<li>&quot;What&#39;s your liability insurance coverage?&quot; (Minimum $1M required)</li>
<li>&quot;Do you carry workers compensation insurance?&quot; (Required by law)</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>4. Installation process:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>&quot;Will you perform a structural evaluation before installation?&quot;</li>
<li>&quot;What&#39;s your typical timeline for a 2,000 sq ft tile roof?&quot;</li>
<li>&quot;How do you handle unexpected deck damage discovered during installation?&quot;</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Red flags:</strong></p>
<p>✗ No specific tile roofing experience
✗ Unlicensed or unwilling to provide license number
✗ No references or portfolio of tile work
✗ Significantly lower price than other quotes (cutting corners)
✗ Pressure to sign immediately without review period</p>
<p><strong>Green flags:</strong></p>
<p>✓ 10+ years tile roofing experience in South Florida
✓ Licensed CCC or CGC contractor
✓ Multiple HVHZ tile installation references
✓ Detailed written proposal explaining HVHZ requirements
✓ Provides Miami-Dade NOA documentation for all products
✓ Discusses structural evaluation and permitting upfront</p>
