<h2>Addressing Common Concerns</h2>
<p><strong>Tile roofing misconceptions and realities.</strong></p>
<h3>Weight and Structural Requirements</h3>
<p><strong>Concern:</strong> &quot;My home was built with shingles. Can it support tile?&quot;</p>
<p><strong>Reality:</strong></p>
<p>Many homes built with shingles CAN support tile roofing with proper evaluation:</p>
<p>✓ <strong>Modern construction (post-1992):</strong> Most homes designed for tile capacity even if originally roofed with shingles
✓ <strong>Rafter sizing:</strong> 2x6 or 2x8 rafters at 24&quot; spacing typically adequate for tile
✓ <strong>Trusses:</strong> Engineered trusses designed for specific load capacity (review original engineering)</p>
<p><strong>When reinforcement is needed:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Older homes (pre-1970s) with 2x4 rafters</li>
<li>Rafters spaced wider than 24&quot; on center</li>
<li>Visible sagging or deflection in existing roof</li>
<li>Long unsupported rafter spans (18+ feet)</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Reinforcement options:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Sister rafters (attach additional rafter alongside existing)</li>
<li>Add intermediate support (ridge beam, collar ties)</li>
<li>Upgrade to engineered trusses (extreme cases, expensive)</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Cost of reinforcement: $2,000-8,000</strong> depending on extent needed</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>Hire structural engineer ($500-1,000) to evaluate your roof framing before committing to tile. Engineer provides stamped letter confirming adequacy or specifying required reinforcement.</p>
<h3>Tile Breakage and Replacement</h3>
<p><strong>Concern:</strong> &quot;Won&#39;t tiles break easily from branches or foot traffic?&quot;</p>
<p><strong>Reality:</strong></p>
<p>Tile is durable but can break under impact or concentrated pressure:</p>
<p><strong>Causes of tile breakage:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Falling tree branches during storms</li>
<li>Foot traffic (walking on roof for maintenance)</li>
<li>Hail (large hail 2&quot;+ diameter)</li>
<li>Installation errors (over-tightened fasteners, improper handling)</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Frequency:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Well-installed tile on maintained property: 5-10 broken tiles over 50 years</li>
<li>Properties with overhanging trees: 10-20 broken tiles over 50 years</li>
<li>Hurricane damage: 0-50+ tiles depending on storm severity</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Replacement is simple:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Lift surrounding tiles carefully</li>
<li>Remove broken tile</li>
<li>Install new replacement tile</li>
<li>Secure with fastener and foam adhesive</li>
<li>Cost: $15-30 per tile + $100-200 service call</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Compare to shingle damage:</strong></p>
<p>Shingle damage requires replacing entire section (50-100 sq ft minimum) because:</p>
<ul>
<li>Individual shingles aren&#39;t replaceable (sealed together)</li>
<li>Color matching is difficult (old shingles faded)</li>
<li>Disturbing one shingle damages adjacent shingles</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Tile advantage:</strong> Localized, inexpensive repairs vs large section replacements</p>
<h3>Upfront Cost Concerns</h3>
<p><strong>Concern:</strong> &quot;Tile costs $25,000. Shingles cost $15,000. That&#39;s $10,000 more I don&#39;t have.&quot;</p>
<p><strong>Reality check:</strong></p>
<p><strong>Option 1: Finance the difference</strong></p>
<p>Many homeowners finance tile premium through:</p>
<ul>
<li>Home equity line of credit (HELOC)</li>
<li>Contractor financing programs</li>
<li>Personal loan</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>$10,000 financed at 6% interest over 10 years:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Monthly payment: $111</li>
<li><strong>Insurance savings: $100-120/month</strong> (nearly pays for itself)</li>
<li>Energy savings: $50-60/month</li>
<li><strong>Net monthly cost: -$40 to +$11</strong> (tile SAVES money monthly)</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Option 2: Total cost of ownership perspective</strong></p>
<p>Over 25 years (halfway through tile&#39;s lifespan):</p>
<p><strong>Shingle roof:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Initial: $15,000</li>
<li>Replacement at year 18: $18,000</li>
<li>Maintenance: $4,000</li>
