</ul>
<p><strong>Tile saves $7,000 by year 25</strong> despite higher initial cost</p>
<p><strong>Option 3: Insurance claim consideration</strong></p>
<p>If you experience hurricane roof damage with shingles:</p>
<ul>
<li>New roof cost: $15,000</li>
<li>Deductible: $2,500-5,000 (typical hurricane deductible 2-5%)</li>
<li><strong>Out-of-pocket: $2,500-5,000</strong></li>
<li>Premium increases: $500-1,000/year for 3-5 years</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Installing tile NOW:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Cost premium: $10,000</li>
<li><strong>Avoid future hurricane claim: Priceless</strong></li>
</ul>
<h3>Installation Timeline</h3>
<p><strong>Concern:</strong> &quot;How long will I be without a roof?&quot;</p>
<p><strong>Reality:</strong></p>
<p><strong>Tile roof installation timeline (2,000 sq ft home):</strong></p>
<p><strong>Day 1:</strong> Tear-off and deck inspection</p>
<ul>
<li>Remove old roofing</li>
<li>Inspect and repair deck</li>
<li>Install base underlayment layer</li>
<li>Temporary weather protection if necessary</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Day 2:</strong> Underlayment and preparation</p>
<ul>
<li>Complete two-layer underlayment system</li>
<li>Install valley flashing</li>
<li>Set battens (if required for tile profile)</li>
<li>Prepare for tile installation</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Day 3-4:</strong> Tile installation</p>
<ul>
<li>Field tile installation with foam adhesive and mechanical fasteners</li>
<li>Hip and ridge tile installation</li>
<li>Precise cutting and fitting around penetrations</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Day 5:</strong> Completion and cleanup</p>
<ul>
<li>Final inspections</li>
<li>Ridge cap securing</li>
<li>Cleanup and debris removal</li>
<li>Final walkthrough</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Total: 5-7 days typical</strong> (longer for larger or complex homes)</p>
<p><strong>Weather delays possible:</strong></p>
<p>South Florida afternoon storms may delay progress 1-2 days. Experienced contractors monitor weather constantly and pause work when rain threatens.</p>
<p><strong>During installation:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Your home remains weatherproof each night (completed sections, temporary coverage)</li>
<li>You can continue living in home during project</li>
<li>Noise and disruption limited to work hours (typically 7am-5pm)</li>
</ul>
